{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"51"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"51","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/51"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.56,0.08,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"51"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112502"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"51","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/51"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"51"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94536"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"129"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3583"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressively worsening double vision and drooping of his right eyelid. He has a history of poorly controlled hypertension and takes amlodipine. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 85/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is complete ptosis of the right upper eyelid. When the lid is lifted, the right eye is deviated down and outward (Image). The right pupil is dilated and poorly reactive to light. The left eye and remaining cranial nerve examination are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of the aneurysm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cerebral artery","Posterior communicating artery","Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Basilar artery","Middle cerebral artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of oculomotor nerve palsy: ptosis, mydriasis (dilated pupil), and a \u0027down and out\u0027 position of the affected eye. When these signs develop acutely, particularly with pupillary involvement, they strongly suggest compression of the oculomotor nerve by an expanding aneurysm. The oculomotor nerve emerges from the brainstem between the posterior cerebral artery and superior cerebellar artery, then passes forward between the posterior communicating artery and the uncus of the temporal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior communicating artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysms are the most common cause of isolated oculomotor nerve palsy with pupillary involvement. The nerve runs in close proximity to this artery, and the pupillomotor fibres run superficially in the nerve, making them particularly vulnerable to compression. This explains why pupillary involvement is an early and prominent sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysms are located in the posterior fossa and are anatomically distant from the course of the oculomotor nerve. These typically present with lateral medullary syndrome or other posterior circulation symptoms rather than isolated cranial nerve palsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysms are anatomically distant from the course of the oculomotor nerve and typically present with symptoms related to the anterior cerebral circulation territory rather than cranial nerve palsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasilar artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysms, while anatomically close to the brainstem, typically cause multiple cranial nerve palsies and brainstem signs rather than an isolated third nerve palsy due to their central location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysms are the most common site for berry aneurysms overall, but these typically present with sudden severe headache from subarachnoid haemorrhage or with focal neurological deficits related to the middle cerebral artery territory (hemiparesis, hemisensory loss, aphasia, or neglect) rather than isolated cranial nerve palsies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Berry aneurysm of the posterior communicating artery commonly presents with an isolated oculomotor (III) nerve palsy.","The classic triad of oculomotor nerve palsy is ptosis, mydriasis, and \u0027down and out\u0027 position of the eye.","Acute onset oculomotor nerve palsy with pupillary involvement requires urgent neuroimaging to exclude posterior communicating artery aneurysm."],"references":["Bolton N, Gushchin A, Williams K. 2. Acquired third nerve palsy. Disease-a-Month. 2021;67(5):101131."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"51"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17475"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17475"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg",